Photo by Ami Vitale @amivitale | Children sit inside Dariya Khan Ghhumnat Rahat camp, set up outside a school in the state of Gujarat in Ahmedabad, India in 2002. They were displaced after some of the worst communal riots in India's history broke out. For days, mobs rampaged the city, burning houses, looting shops, raping women, and killing men, women and children. 
While this crisis has passed, there are 40 million internally displaced persons around the world who, while remaining in their own county, have no specific legal status or special protections, and are often at risk of being caught in the cross fire or used as pawns, targets, and human shields. Women and girls are among the most vulnerable. You can help by following those that try to help those currently displaced, like @doctorswithoutborders @ICRC and @refugees
